ICD-10
------

ICD-10 is the tenth edition of the International Statistical Classification of Diseases
and Related Health Problems, published by the WHO.

Data was downloaded and imported from [0] (**December 2025 update** the link has moved here [1]).  We don't know how often new releases are
published.

Download the latest release.  Select the ClaML format to download (ClaML is a an XML-based format, designed for classifications). It will be downloaded as a zipped .xml file, named e.g.
`icdClaML2019ens.zip`.  In the absence of a more specific release date, we label it as valid from the 1st of the year of release.

The version can be retrieved from the `<Title>` tag of the XML file.  Usually this is just a year; 2019 includes extra COVID extensions and is labelled 2019-covid-expanded.

To import the data, run:

        ./manage.py import_coding_system_data icd10
        path/to/zip/file/in/dokku/app
        --release <release_name> --valid-from YYYY-MM-DD --import-ref <ref>

- `release` is a short label for this coding system release - the version reference as
  described above.
- `valid-from` is the date that this release is valid from (NOT the date it is being
  imported into OpenCodelists), in YYYY-MM-DD format
- `import-ref` is an optional long-form reference field for any other potential
  references or comments on this import if desired. Include at least the full downloaded
  zipfile here.

For the example above (`icdClaML2019ens.zip`), the data should be
imported with:

    dokku run opencodelists python manage.py import_coding_system_data icd10
    /storage/data/icd10/icdClaML2019ens.zip
    --release 2019-covid-expanded
    --valid-from 2019-01-01
    --import-ref icdClaML2019ens.zip

After importing, restart the opencodelists app with:

    dokku ps:restart opencodelists

[0] https://apps.who.int/classifications/apps/icd/ClassificationDownload/DLArea/Download.aspx
[1] https://icdcdn.who.int/icd10/index.html


## Combined edition release process

### In words

1. Scrape the data from the NHS Classification Browser and convert to ClaML (using `./scripts/TODO.py`).
2. This will produce a ClaML file (`./data/TODO.xml`)
3. Check if the scraped data has changed since the last time we ran this process (via git diff). If it has, skip to step 8, otherwise continue.
4. Run `python -m coding_systems.icd10.scripts.check_icd10_claml_zip_timestamps` to check the last_modified timestamps and file sizes of the 2016 and 2019 WHO ClaML files.
5. This produces a JSON file (`./data/claml_metadata.json`) with the last_modified timestamps and file sizes of the 2016 and 2019 WHO ClaML files.
6. If the 2016 WHO ClaML file has changed (via git diff) since the last time we ran this process, then skip to step 8. Otherwise continue.
7. If the 2019 WHO ClaML file has changed (via git diff) since the last time we ran this process, then skip to step 9. Otherwise continue.
8. Run the script `python -m coding_systems.icd10.scripts.compare_2016_claml_with_scraped` to check the assumptions we make about the differences between the 2016 WHO ClaML file and the scraped file, and fix any issues if necessary.
9. Run the script `python -m coding_systems.icd10.scripts.compare_2016_combined_with_2019_claml` to check the assumptions we make about the differences between the combined 2016 WHO + NHS ClaML file and the 2019 WHO ClaML file, and fix any issues if necessary.
10. Create a new combined release with the updated data.

### In flowchart form

```mermaid
---
title: Combined edition release process
---
flowchart TD
    scraper[Script to scrape the data from the <a href='https://classbrowser.nhs.uk/#/book/ICD-10-5TH-Edition'>NHS Classification Browser</a> and convert to ClaML]
    scraped_output[./data/2016_scraped_claml.xml]
    scraped_diff{Has the<br>scraped data<br>changed?}
    last_modified[Script to extract the last_modified date from the zip files at <a href='https://icdcdn.who.int/icd10/index.html'>https://icdcdn.who.int/icd10/index.html</a> ./scripts/check_icd10_claml_zip_timestamps.py]
    2016_change{Has the<br>2016 claml<br>file changed?}
    2019_change{Has the<br>2019 claml<br>file changed?}
    last_mod_output[./data/claml_metadata.json]
    do_nothing[Nothing to do<br>or maybe record somewhere that no changes were detected?]
    K[Run script to check 2016 scraped on claml assumptions and fix if necessary ./scripts/compare_2016_claml_with_scraped.py]
    L[Run script to check 2016 to 2019 assumptions and fix if necessary ./scripts/compare_2016_combined_with_2019_claml.py]
    M[Create new combined release]
    scraper -->|Produces| scraped_output
    scraped_output --> scraped_diff
    scraped_diff -->|No| last_modified
    scraped_diff -->|Yes| K
    last_modified -->|Produces| last_mod_output
    last_mod_output --> 2016_change
    2016_change -->|No| 2019_change
    2016_change -->|Yes| K
    2019_change -->|No| do_nothing
    2019_change -->|Yes| L
    K --> L
    L --> M

```
